===Etymology 1===
Old English ''[[feohtan]]'', from West Germanic ''*fextanan''. Cognate with Dutch ''[[vechten]]'', German ''[[fechten]]''.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|fights|fighting|fought|'''[[fought]]''' ''or (archaic)'' '''[[foughten]]'''}}

# {{intransitive}} To [[contend]] in physical conflict, either singly or in war, battle etc.
#:''The two boxers have been '''fighting''' for more than half an hour.''
#:''A wounded animal will '''fight''' like a maniac.''
# {{intransitive}} To [[strive]] for; to campaign or [[contend]] for success.
#:''He '''fought''' for the Democrats in the last election.''
# {{transitive}} To conduct or engage in (battle, warfare etc.).
#:''The battle was '''fought''' just over that hill.''
# {{transitive}} To engage in combat; to oppose physically, to contest with.
#:''My grandfather '''fought''' the Nazis in the Second World War.''
# {{transitive}} To [[try]] to [[overpower]]; to [[fiercely]] [[counteract]].
#:''The government pledged to '''fight''' corruption.''

